gency_COVID-19.pdf|title=Declaration of Local Emergency by the Local Director of Emergency Management and Consent of the Board of Supervisors of Warren County|location=[[Front Royal, Virginia]]|publisher=[[Warren County, Virginia]] Government|accessdate=March 29, 2020|quote=THEREFORE, the Chairman of the Board of Supervisors, Walter J. Mabe, is the Local Director of Emergency Management (the \"Local Director\") and declares that a local emergency exists in Warren County pursuant to Code of Virginia \u00a7 44-146.21. THEREFORE, the Warren County Board of Supervisors consents to the Local Director's declaration of local emergency pursuant to Code of Virginia \u00a7 44-146.21.}}</ref> The [[Page County, Virginia|Page County]] Board of Supervisors approved a resolution containing a declaration of a local emergency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pagecounty.virginia.gov/DocumentCenter/View/2468/PageCountyLocalEmergencyDeclaration_COVID19|title=Resolution: Declaration Of A Local Emergency|date=March 17, 2020|location=[[Luray, Virginia]]|publisher=[[Page County, Virginia]], Government|accessdate=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329213122/https://www.pagecounty.virginia.gov/DocumentCenter/View/2468/PageCountyLocalEmergencyDeclaration_COVID19|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Shenandoah County, Virginia|Shenandoah County]] Administrator declared a local emergency, which the County's Board of Supervisors was scheduled to ratify on March 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shenandoahcountyva.us/administration/2020/03/shenandoah-county-declares-local-emergency/|title=Shenandoah County Declares Local Emergency|work=Media Release|date=March 17, 2020|location=[[Woodstock, Virginia]]|publisher=[[Shenandoah County, Virginia]] Government|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The Mayor and City Council of the [[Fairfax, Virginia|City of Fairfax]] adopted a declaration of local emergency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fairfaxva.gov/Home/Components/News/News/9914/18|title=Declaration of Local Emergency - COVID 19, City of Fairfax, Virginia|work=News|date=March 18, 2020|publisher=[[Fairfax, Virginia|City of Fairfax, Virginia]] Government|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The [[Manassas, Virginia|Manassas]] City Manager signed a declaration of local state of emergency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidenova.com/news/prince_william/local/manassas/manassas-declares-state-of-emergency/article_cfb38be4-688f-11ea-a8a6-dbf655e65359.html|title=Manassas declares state of emergency|work=InsideNova|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=InsideNoVa.com|accessdate=March 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319200053/https://www.insidenova.com/news/prince_william/local/manassas/manassas-declares-state-of-emergency/article_cfb38be4-688f-11ea-a8a6-dbf655e65359.html|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The interim City Manager of [[Winchester, Virginia|Winchester]] declared a state of emergency for the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.winchesterva.gov/city-manager-declares-state-emergency-coronavirus-pandemic|title=City Manager declares State of Emergency for Coronavirus pandemic|date=March 17, 2020|publisher=City of [[Winchester, Virginia]], Government|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n:'''March 18''': The [[Leesburg, Virginia|Leesburg]] Town Council consented to a declaration of local emergency to be issued by the Town Manager, acting in his capacity as the Director of Emergency Management.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://loudounnow.com/2020/03/18/leesburg-declares-local-emergency-downtown-parking-now-free/|title=Leesburg Declares Local Emergency; Downtown Parking Now Free|work=LoudounNow|date=March 18, 2020|publisher=LoudounNow.com|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n:'''March 19''': The [[Frederick County, Virginia|Frederick County]] Administrator declared a state of emergency.<ref>{{cite web|last=Janey|first=Josh|date=March 20, 2020|url=https://www.winchesterstar.com/coronavirus/frederick-county-declares-state-of-emergency/article_031146bb-cf23-5335-a939-3b99e9ae7b7d.html|title=Frederick County declares state of emergency|location=[[Winchester, Virginia]]|publisher=[[The Winchester Star]]|accessdate=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322174532/https://www.winchesterstar.com/coronavirus/frederick-county-declares-state-of-emergency/article_031146bb-cf23-5335-a939-3b99e9ae7b7d.html|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n:'''March 23''': The [[Front Royal]] Town Council declared a \"COVID-19 Emergency Ordinance\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Roger|last=Bianchini|date=March 24, 2020|url=https://royalexaminer.com/front-royal-joins-county-in-declaring-covid-19-emergency/|title=Front Royal joins County in declaring COVID-19 Emergency|location=[[Front Royal, Virginia]]|publisher=Royal Examiner|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the afternoon of March 17, Governor Northam issued an order allowing law enforcement to enforce a ban on gatherings of more than 10 people in public spaces; earlier in the day, he had appeared unwilling to take such measures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/maryland-virginia-sees-jump-in-coronavirus-cases/|title=Va. to enforce 10-person limit in some businesses, as DC area sees jump in coronavirus cases|date=March 17, 2020|website=WTOP|accessdate=March 18, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318032045/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/maryland-virginia-sees-jump-in-coronavirus-cases/|archivedate=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some restaurant owners had previously expressed dissatisfaction with the lack of direction provided by the government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/food/article/21123147/diners-are-still-eating-out-in-alexandria-as-virginia-hesitates-to-close-restaurants|title=Diners Are Still Eating Out in Alexandria as Virginia Hesitates to Close Restaurants|website=Washington City Paper|accessdate=March 19, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319154825/https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/food/article/21123147/diners-are-still-eating-out-in-alexandria-as-virginia-hesitates-to-close-restaurants|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Virginia officials asked law enforcement to avoid arrests where possible. The administration also asked magistrates and judges to consider alternatives to incarceration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.richmond.com/news/virginia/update-virginia-officials-asking-law-enforcement-to-avoid-arrests-when/article_67dbe141-da92-504b-b74d-e7c9ed8a118c.html|title=UPDATE: Virginia officials asking law enforcement to avoid arrests when possible|last=|first=|website=Richmond Times-Dispatch|language=en|access-date=2020-03-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320061816/https://www.richmond.com/news/virginia/update-virginia-officials-asking-law-enforcement-to-avoid-arrests-when/article_67dbe141-da92-504b-b74d-e7c9ed8a118c.html|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Northam issued an order that banned within Virginia all gatherings of more than 10 people.  The order required all public schools to be closed for the remainder of the current school year. The order also closed certain types of businesses, such as bowling alleys, gyms, and theaters.<ref name=March23>(1) {{cite web|date=March 23, 2020|url=https://www.nbc29.com/2020/03/23/gov-northam-schools-remain-closed-through-academic-year/|title=Gov. Northam cancels school year, orders some businesses closed|location=[[Charlottesville, Virginia]]|publisher=[[WVIR-TV|NBC29.COM]]|language=en-US|accessdate=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325044530/https://www.nbc29.com/2020/03/23/gov-northam-schools-remain-closed-through-academic-year/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=https://www.governor.virginia.gov/newsroom/all-releases/2020/march/headline-855292-en.html|title=Governor Northam Orders Statewide Closure of Certain Non-Essential Businesses, K-12 Schools|work=News Release|date=March 23, 2020|5=|location=Richmond, Virginia|publisher=Commonwealth of Virginia: Office of the [[Governor of Virginia|Governor]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326232345/https://www.governor.virginia.gov/newsroom/all-releases/2020/march/headline-855292-en.html|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Northam|first=Ralph|date=March 23, 2020|author-link=Ralph Northam|url=https://www.governor.virginia.gov/media/governorvirginiagov/executive-actions/EO-53-Temporary-Restrictions-Due-To-Novel-Coronavirus-(COVID-19).pdf|title=Executive Order Number Fifty-Three (2020): Temporary Restrictions on Restaurants, Recreational, Entertainment, Gatherings, Non-Essential Retail Businesses, and Closure of K-12 Schools Due To Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|location=Richmond, Virginia|publisher=Commonwealth of Virginia: Office of the [[Governor of Virginia|Governor]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327194854/https://www.governor.virginia.gov/media/governorvirginiagov/executive-actions/EO-53-Temporary-Restrictions-Due-To-Novel-Coronavirus-%28COVID-19%29.pdf|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe March 23 order closed \"dining and congregation areas\" in restaurants, dining establishments, food courts, farmers markets, breweries, microbreweries, distilleries, wineries and tasting rooms, but left open all other areas in those types of businesses. The order also left open certain specified \"essential retail businesses\" including pharmacies, grocery stores, and banks (among others).<ref name=March23/> On March 26, an Alexandria pub \u2014 that a COVID-19 positive person had visited on March 10, March 14, and March 15 \u2014 reportedly said on its [[Facebook]] page that it was closed only through March 28 for cleaning and sanitizing.<ref>{{cite web|first=Emily|last=Leayman|date=March 26, 2020|url=https://patch.com/virginia/delray/s/h28ne/person-with-coronavirus-visited-alexandria-pub-exposure-possible?utm_source=alert-breakingnews&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=alert|title=Person With Coronavirus Visited Alexandria Pub, Exposure Possible|publisher=[[List of neighborhoods in Alexandria, Virginia#Del Ray|Del Ray, Virginia]], Patch|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNortham's March 23 order did not define construction activity as being \"essential\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Northam|first=Ralph|date=March 23, 2020|author-link=Ralph Northam|url=https://www.governor.virginia.gov/media/governorvirginiagov/executive-actions/EO-53-Temporary-Restrictions-Due-To-Novel-Coronavirus-(COVID-19).pdf|title=Executive Order Number Fifty-Three (2020): Temporary Restrictions on Restaurants, Recreational, Entertainment, Gatherings, Non-Essential Retail Businesses, and Closure of K-12 Schools Due To Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|location=Richmond, Virginia|publisher=Commonwealth of Virginia: Office of the [[Governor of Virginia|Governor]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327194854/https://www.governor.virginia.gov/media/governorvirginiagov/executive-actions/EO-53-Temporary-Restrictions-Due-To-Novel-Coronavirus-%28COVID-19%29.pdf|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' reported on March 28 that the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia had designated construction as well as several other types of businesses as essential. The ''Post'' reported that construction projects were still underway in those jurisdictions and that a spokesperson for Northam had claimed that the federal government had determined that construction is essential.<ref name=Lazo>{{cite news|first1=Luz|last1=Lazo|first2=Katherine|last2=Shaver|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|title=Work on region\u2019s big projects continues amid coronavirus, with construction an \u2018essential\u2019 business|work=Transportation|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401022830/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Post'' also reported that the State of Washington's transportation department had suspended work on nearly all of its projects and that Washington's governor had clarified his [[stay-at-home order]] to state that construction was not considered an essential activity.<ref name=Lazo/> \n\nThe [[United States Department of Homeland Security]]'s March 28 guidance on essential critical infrastructure lists as \"essential\" the construction of residential/shelter facilities and services, energy-related facilities, communications and information technology, public works including the  construction of critical or strategic infrastructure and infrastructure that is temporarily required to support COVID-19 response, is for certain other types of community- or government-based operations, or is otherwise critical, strategic, or essential. The guidance does not contain any such listings for other types of construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|title=Guidance on the Essential Critical Infrastructure Workforce: Ensuring Community and National Resilience in COVID-19 Response|date=March 28, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[United States Department of Homeland Security]]: [[Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency]]: Office of the Director|accessdate=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402033910/https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, Northam and the State Health Commissioner issued a public health emergency order that prohibited inpatient and outpatient surgical hospitals, free-standing [[endoscopy]] centers, physicians\u2019 offices, and dental, [[Orthodontics|orthodontic]], and [[Endodontics|endodontic]] offices from providing procedures and surgeries that require [[personal protective equipment]] (PPE), which if delayed, are not anticipated to cause harm to the patient by negatively affecting the patient's health outcomes, or leading to disability or death. The prohibition did not include outpatient visits delivered in hospital-based clinics.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://www.governor.virginia.gov/newsroom/all-releases/2020/march/headline-855474-en.html|title=Governor Northam Directs Postponement of Elective Surgeries|work=News Release|date=March 25, 2020|location=Richmond, Virginia|publisher=Commonwealth of Virginia: Office of the Governor|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402091814/https://www.governor.virginia.gov/newsroom/all-releases/2020/march/headline-855474-en.html|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{cite web|first=Caleb|last=Stewart|date=March 26, 2020|url=https://www.whsv.com/content/news/Virginia-Dept-of-Health-confirms-391-COVID-19-cases-across-Virginia-569093411.html|title=Gov. Northam orders elective surgeries postponed with 391 confirmed COVID-19 cases|location=[[Harrisonburg, Virginia]]|publisher=[[WHSV-TV|WHSV-3]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326174427/https://www.whsv.com/content/news/Virginia-Dept-of-Health-confirms-391-COVID-19-cases-across-Virginia-569093411.html|archivedate=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last1=Northam|first1=Ralph E., Governor|last2=Oliver, MPH|first2=M. Norman, MD, MPH, State Health Commissioner|url=https://www.governor.virginia.gov/media/governorvirginiagov/executive-actions/Order-of-Public-Health-Emergency-Two---Order-of-The-Governor-and-State-Health-Commissioner.pdf|title=Order of the Governor and State Health Commissioner: Order of Public Health Emergency Two|date=March 25, 2020|location=Richmond, Virginia|publisher=Commonwealth of Virginia: Executive Department|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327234050/https://www.governor.virginia.gov/media/governorvirginiagov/executive-actions/Order-of-Public-Health-Emergency-Two---Order-of-The-Governor-and-State-Health-Commissioner.pdf|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Northam issued a stay-at-home order, to remain effective until June 10 unless amended or rescinded. The order required everyone to remain at their place of residence, with certain specified exceptions (including traveling to work, to obtain food and for outdoor exercise). The order also required people using shared or outdoor spaces to maintain [[social distancing]] of at least {{convert|6|ft|m|1}} from any other person, with the exception of family or household members or caretakers.<ref name=\"March 30 order\"/>\n\n== Statistics ==\n<!--Do NOT change the disease totals UNLESS YOU HAVE A SOURCE. PERIOD.-->{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Virginia medical cases chart}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"3\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Virginia<ref name=\"VDHSituationSummary1\" /><ref name=\"WSLS-March 27\"/><ref name=\"WTVR-March22\"/>\nUpdated April 4, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |County\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n!Deaths\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Accomack County, Virginia|Accomack County]]\n|8\n|0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;