{"title_page": "John Wackerman", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=John Wackerman|timestamp=20200328213255|year=2020|month=March|day=28|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=John Wackerman|date=28 March 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|Biographies|date=March 2020}}\n{{Third-party|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image =File:John Wackerman october2019.jpg\n| caption =Playing at Hollywood Drum Show, 2019\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=y|1965|6|3}}\n| birth_place = [[Long Beach, California]], U.S.\n| death_date = \n| genre = \n{{flatlist|\n* [[Jazz fusion]]\n* [[pop music]]\n* [[funk metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n}}\n| occupation = Musician, songwriter\n| instrument = Drums, Piano, Vibraphone<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| years_active = 1971\u2013present\n| label = \n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Maynard Ferguson]]\n* [[Kazumi Watanabe]]\n* [[Mass Mental]]\n}}\n| website =\n}}\n\n'''John Wackerman''' (born June 3, 1965) is an American drummer and pianist, son of the musical instructor Chuck Wackerman and brother of the drummers [[Chad Wackerman]] and [[Brooks Wackerman]] and bassist Bob Wackerman.\n\nJohn started taking piano lessons at the age of five, but his real passion for percussion started when his father decided to sell his boat to buy a [[Vibraphone]].\nHe studied<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drumchannel.com/teacher/john-wackerman/|title=John Wackerman Archives}}</ref> with names like: Ruth Ritchie, [[Murray Spivack]], [[Chuck Flores]], [[Charlie Shoemake]] and [[Earl Hatch]].\nAt 16, he joined [[Bill Watrous]] Big Band and from there he started to play with [[Maynard Ferguson]], [[Kazumi Watanabe]], [[Bunny Brunel]], [[Patrick Moraz]] (Moody Blues, [[Yes (band)|Yes]]) and [[Lindsay Buckingham]] ([[Fleetwood Mac]]). He is currently part of a duo with the female singer Echo Maki, the EchoWacko.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/echowackoobviously/|title=EchoWacko (@echowackoobviously)|via=Instagram}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 he released a CD accompanied by a book with transcribed compositions called Drum Duets volume 1. This material has the participation of some notable drummers, such as [[Steve Gadd]], Peter Erskine, Ron Tutt, Clayton Cameron,\n[[Adrian Young]], Steve Smith, [[Josh Freese]], John Ferraro, his younger brother [[Brooks Wackerman]], [[Ricky Lawson]], his father Chuck Wackerman, Alex Acuna, Gary Novak, Marc Atkinson, and his older brother [[Chad Wackerman]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sheetmusicplus.com/title/john-wackerman-drum-duets-volume-1-sheet-music/17689309|title=John Wackerman -- Drum Duets, Volume 1 By John Wackerman - CD Sheet Music For Drumset (Buy Print Music AP.77-5JW1CD From Alfred Music At Sheet Music Plus)|first=John|last=Wackerman|website=sheetmusicplus.com}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n'''With [[Bunny Brunel]]'''\n\n*''Momentum''<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Momentum-Bunny-Brunel/dp/B000CA7C2C</ref> (1989)\n\n'''With [[Kazumi Watanabe]]'''\n\n*''[[Kilowatt (album)]]'' (1989)\n\n'''With [[Mass Mental|Mass Mental?]]'''\n\n*''[[How to Write Love Songs]]'' (1999) - Vibraphone on the track \"I Win\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://instagram.com/johnwackerman Official Instagram page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wackerman, John}}\n[[Category:American drummers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=John Wackerman|times